04745nam a22006855i 9780292772816DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211975txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927728167 a10.7560/7241432doi  a(DE-B1597)587556  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPR883b.F6 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a823/.0300aForms of Modern British Fiction /ced. by Alan Warren Friedman. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1975  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tOne. The Once and Future Age of Modernism: An Introduction -- tTwo. Ethical Structures in John Galsworthy, Elizabeth Bowen, and Iris Murdoch -- tThree. Fiction and Repetition: Tess of the d’Urbervilles -- tFour. D. H. Lawrence’s Dualism: The Apollonian- Dionysian Polarity and The Ladybird -- tFive. Stephen Dedalus and the Spiritual-Heroic Refrigerating Apparatus: Art and Life in Joyce’s Portrait -- tSix. Virginia Woolf: Tradition and Modernity -- tSeven. Fiction at the Edge of Poetry: Durrell, Beckett, Green -- tAppendix: A Panel Discussion -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Forms of Modern British Fiction six individualistic and strongminded critics delineate the "age of modernism" in British fiction. Dating the age and the movement from later Hardy works through the deaths of Joyce and Woolf, they present British fiction as a cohesive, self-contained unit of literary history. Hardy appears as the first of the modern British novelists, Lawrence as the central, and Joyce and Woolf as the last. The writers and the modern movement are framed by precursors, such as Galsworthy, and by successors, Durrell, Beckett, and Henry Green—the postmoderns. The pattern of the essays suggests a growing self-consciousness on the part of twentieth-century writers as they seek not only to refine their predecessors but also to deny (and sometimes obliterate) them. The moderns thus deny the novel itself, a genre once firmly rooted in history and forms of social life. Their works do not assume that comfortable mimetic relationship between the fictive realities of art and life. Consequently, there has now evolved a poetics of the novel that is virtually identifiable with modern fiction, a poetics still highly problematical in its attempt to denote a medium in whose name eclectic innovativeness and incessant revitalizing are proclaimed. Forms of Modern British Fiction refines and advances the discussion of the modern novel and the world it and we inhabit.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aCowan, James C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleishman, Avrom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Alan Warren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Alan Warren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGindin, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, J. Hillis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRossman, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUnterecker, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292772816423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292772816/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-